I get asked allllll the time why I still sell on Etsy even though I only link to/advertise my website. I think it’s the right move for 99% of small businesses that create their own products and here’s why!!

I don’t advertise my Etsy shop at all. There are some customers who ordered from me there before I had a website and still come back, but mostly my sales are from Etsy search results! 

So you might be thinking, what about the crazy fees on Etsy!? And I’m not the biggest fan of the nearly 10% Etsy takes off the top, I’ll be honest, BUT Etsy is bringing in those customers for me, so I’m ok to pay for that service. Marketing is hard, time consuming, exhausting, and expensive, so if Etsy wants 10% to bring in a bunch of customers for me, that’s a price I am willing to pay.

If your margins can handle the fees (and they should be able to, because otherwise you might be under charging!) and you have the supply (aka you aren’t always selling out of your products) then I totally recommend selling on Etsy, too. It’s always nice to have more sales and reach more people without much extra work!!

Was this helpful? I’m hoping this year I get the chance to share more about my business decisions and offer some more advice/suggestions as well, so let me know if y’all would be interested in that 🥰

Storytime!!

This was my *very first* viral tiktok from way back in 2020. It was the first time I realized “wow tiktok could be an amazing tool for my business” and it motivated me to keep making and posting my art there. Something I didn’t fully realize until now, though, is how sharing my work on tiktok (and on instagram) made me want to become a better artist. I taught myself new things and improved sooo much at painting and digital art, too. 

Now looking back, I realized that sort of symbiosis between creativity and my social media channels all got lost in the building of my business, and I really miss it. 

Making art takes SO much time, so it’s easy to put it on the back burner. But I think seeing the art from start for finish is what has made my business a little different from other stationery brands and hopefully also fun to follow along with. 

Hopefully I can get back into it and share more ideas, more projects, and more ART🎨 and I really hope that’s what y’all want to see from me too :)
my new favorite place 🥰🧊

Getting my art stolen over and over again has been SO emotionally taxing. And when I say that, I really don’t mean seeing other people creating similar art to mine; I’m talking straight up screenshotting and tracing. 

I’ve reached out to A LOT of people who have copied my art and often they say “I didn’t realize it was yours” or “I just got it off Pinterest” so I’m here to tell you: every piece of art was made by and belongs to someone (at least until AI art takes over and ruins everything 😳). 

So if you see a piece of art anywhere, know that someone labored over it for a good chunk of their day, week, year…or maybe even over a good chunk of their life. And the fact that someone sat down, thought up a piece, made it with their fingers or their hands or their body, spent hours thinking about each detail—that’s what makes art special. I hate that people don’t see the value in that and treat stealing and copying so flippantly. It breaks my heart a little every time I see art stolen, mine or other’s. And let me tell you, even thought I know how to handle it legally, it doesn’t get any easier.

I hope that eventually we’ll reach a point where everyone understands that art comes not from somewhere, like Pinterest, but from someONE.

I’m in the LATimes this morning!! 

A reporter reached out to me last week to talk about the effect a TikTok ban would have on small business owners. As a lot of you know, I’ve been able to grow my business over the past 3 years in large part thanks to TikTok and Instagram. I’m definitely worried about the impact that a TikTok ban would have on my business since it’s one of the main ways I reach my customers. Honestly, I’d be lying if I said I wasn’t dreading that possibility and scared for what would follow. But if it happens, I’ll just be counting on y’all who have been here supporting me on Instagram a little bit more. I’m so immensely thankful for everyone who has followed my journey and supported my business over the past few years and I can only hope that y’all will be willing to stick around even if TikTok doesn’t 🙃

If you want to, you all can always follow me over on my YouTube channel to see more of my content. That’s probably where I’ll be showing up even more should TikTok be banned.

Happy May!!! It’s the month of my wedding so I’m more than a little excited AND anxious seeing that calendar page flip.. 🥲 

The beginning of a new month felt like the perfect time to show off the new birth month flower stickers I made a few weeks back! I looooove how they turned out—especially the lily of the valley for May and larkspur for July! I have a June birthday but I’ve never been a rose person so I think I’m going to claim July for myself, don’t tell 👀

Anyway, I have all these new clear stickers up on my website now AND I’ve already been getting a lot of questions about using these flowers for tattoos! So I added a “tattoo permission” listing to my website where you can get a license to use one of my designs for that! (Links are in my bio as usual!!) 

As y’all know, using artists’ work without permission is copyright infringement, but I didn’t want to make it hard to get my permission/consent to use one of my designs for a tattoo since that is truly such a huge honor for me! 

And if anyone wants a semi-custom drawn bouquet of birth month flowers, just reach out and message or email me, I’d be happy to consider it!! 

With all that said, I hope you all love these little flowers as much as I do!

I had a lot of anxiety about these calendars thinking there might be imperfections of some kind, and somehow I still missed it. Usually with misprinted items, it’s a result of a miscommunication or manufacturing error, but this one is on me because I didn’t catch it in the sample. I feel pretty terrible that we released this calendar without realizing the odd formatting it has, so we’re offering refunds to those who paid full price—just send us an email. I really try to be transparent about these mistakes because I always want to make them right and don’t want anyone thinking they can’t trust the products we put out. That’s why I wanted to post this, to reach y’all who bought one initially. Again, I feel really awful about the whole thing, so please reach out if you got one of these calendars. Better believe I’ll be much more on top of them for next year 😔
